external.description: विवेक अग्निहोत्री की बहुप्रतीक्षित फिल्म द बंगाल फाइल्स अब सिनेमाघरों में दस्तक देने को तैयार है — इसकी रिलीज़ डेट तय हो चुकी है: 5 सितंबर 2025 । यह फिल्म ‘द फाइल्स’ ट्रिलॉजी की तीसरी कड़ी है, जिसमें पहले ‘द कश्मीर फाइल्स’ और ‘द ताशकंद फाइल्स’ पहले ही रिलीज हो चुके हैं। इस फिल्म में 1946 की बंगाल की घटित डायरेक्ट एक्शन डे साम्प्रदायिक हिंसा को एक काल्पनिक वर्तमान CBI जांच से जोड़कर प्रस्तुत किया गया है। राजनीतिक विरोध और थिएटरों में रोक फिल्म की रिलीज से पहले ही विवाद उठ खड़ा हुआ है — विशेषकर पश्चिम बंगाल में। निर्देशक अग्निहोत्री का आरोप है कि राज्य सरकार और पुलिस की धमकीमयी कार्रवाई के चलते कई थिएटर मालिक इसे नहीं दिखाना चाहते। उन्होंने इसको “गैर-लागू और असंवैधानिक” बताया और कानूनी कार्रवाई की तैयारी का संकेत दिया है। निर्माता पल्लवी जोशी ने राष्ट्रपति से इस ‘अनौपचारिक प्रतिबंध’ से रक्षा की अपील की है ।

A Skeptic’s Guide to #ArtificialIntelligence, with @GaryMarcus.bsky.social

external.description: Many of us are increasingly confronted by the worry that we are living through the backstory of some sci-fi dystopia. Wealth inequality is skyrocketing, and some of the richest billionaires are heading AI companies with the goal of creating superintelligence. People like OpenAI’s Sam Altman and Anthropic’s Dario Amodei speak openly about the potential for mass unemployment once their products—LLMs called ChatGPT and Claude, respectively—start taking over the jobs of humans. Are they right? Is this a future worth wanting?Gary Marcus doesn’t think so. In this salon, we’ll explore why with one of the most recognized and respected commentators on the science and business of AI. He’s well-known for his challenges to today’s AI systems, like chatbots and Tesla’s self-driving software, and has anticipated many of the current limitations decades in advance. Plus, his research has recently been cited in Disney and Universal’s legal case against Midjourney, an AI image generator.Before he became one of the most prolific and insightful voices pushing back against AI hype, Marcus was a cognitive scientist at New York University and entrepreneur. He sold his company, Geometric Intelligence, to Uber and has authored five books, including The Algebraic Mind, Kluge, The Birth of the Mind, the New York Times Bestseller Guitar Zero, and most recently Taming Silicon Valley: How We Can Ensure That AI Works for Us.This discussion is for anyone feeling curious or concerned about what AIs today are capable of, and how AI companies plan on using them to transform our society. Experts are welcome—we’ll look forward to hearing Marcus respond to critiques of his work—but this conversation is for non-experts as well. Marcus is, after all, a skilled communicator of complex ideas. His work has appeared in places like Nautilus, Wired, and The New Yorker, and you can find most of his writing now on Substack: Marcus on AI.Come ready for a stimulating gathering on why AI may be overhyped in the short-term but underhyped in the long-term!To read:Deep Learning Is Hitting a WallHow and Why Gary Marcus Became AI's Leading CriticThe “AI 2027” Scenario: How realistic is it?
